DIV1.P:
VER. 81—84. Slander—libell'd by her hate.] There seems to be more spirit here than in the original. But it is hard to pro∣nounce with certainty. For tho' one may be confident there is more force in the 83d and 84th lines than in

Canidia Albuti, quibus est inimica, venenum;
yet there might be something, for ought we know, in the Cha∣racter or History of Cervius which might bring up that line to the spirit of poinancy of the 82d verse of the Imitation.

VER. 44. Yet Time ennobles, or degrades each Line; It bright∣en'd Craggs's, and may darken thine,] One of the noblest houses in Europe.—The Original is,
Quicquid sub terra est, in apricum proferet aetas;
Defodiet, condetque nitentia. This wants neither force nor elegance; yet is vastly inferior to the imitation, where a very fine panegyric on two great Cha∣racters, in the second line, gives dignity and ease to the mas∣terly conciseness of the first.
